### Issue #7: Shorten the accessible name of blog-post links

**Type:** Quality Issue

**Location:** Home page, "From my blog" section.

**Steps to reproduce:**
1. Open the Home page.
2. Inspect the blog-post cards in the "From my blog" column.
3. Observe that each entire card is a single link.

**Observed behavior:** Each blog card is one link whose accessible name concatenates the post title, the excerpt, the author name, and the date — for example, the full string "AI Heuristic Evaluation: Building a UX Claude skill … I built a Claude skill for conducting usability heuristic evaluations … DANIELA NAPOLI MAY 18" is read as one link name.

**Why it matters:** A screen-reader user navigating by links, or pulling up a links list, hears a long, run-together block instead of a crisp, scannable title. It does not break the link — it still works — so this is a Quality Issue, but it weakens the "links list" navigation affordance and relates to WCAG 2.4.4 (Link Purpose).

**Expert perspectives:**
- **Steve Krug (simulated):** *"A link name should be a label, not a paragraph. If I can't tell where it goes in a breath, it's too long."* — Adds the radical-clarity lens.
- **Per Axbom (simulated):** *"Sighted users skim the card; screen-reader users get the whole card poured into one link name. Same component, very different experience."* — Adds the inclusion lens.
- **Steve Portigal (simulated):** *"Watch how people actually consume a blog list — they triage by title. The link name should match that real behavior."* — Adds the research-grounded behavioral lens.

**Severity — FMEA (Soares):**
- S: 2 — Minor; the link works, but it is verbose and harder to triage by ear.
- O: 3 — Affects assistive-technology users on the Home page.
- D: 5 — Detectable with a screen reader or a links-list check; not caught by visual QA.
- **RPN: 30 (Low)**

**Severity — Nielsen:** 1 — Cosmetic; fix if time permits.

**Discrepancy flags:** None of note. FMEA (Low) and Nielsen (cosmetic) agree.

**Verification status:** Rendered browser ✓ — concatenated link text confirmed via live DOM inspection of the blog-card anchors.

**Prevalence / context:** Common. "Whole card is one link" is a widespread pattern; the accessible-name bloat it creates is a routine accessibility finding, relating to WCAG Success Criterion 2.4.4 (Link Purpose, In Context).

**Recommendation:**
- **Primary fix:** Make the post *title* the link, and keep the excerpt, author, and date as adjacent non-link text within the card.
- **Stretch fix:** If the whole card should remain clickable, give the anchor an explicit `aria-label` of just the post title, or use a title link with the card click handled as an enhancement.

