## 3. Patterns & Themes

**Systemic vs. surface.** Most of what surfaced is surface-level polish that is quick to fix (card heights, footer clutter, link text, the 404 template). One pattern is closer to systemic: **accessibility is implemented inconsistently.** The site clearly had accessibility in mind — a working skip link, a correct `lang` attribute, visible focus outlines, descriptive image alt text, `prefers-reduced-motion` support, and `rel="noopener"` on external links are all present and are genuinely above average for a personal site. But three separate findings (heading structure, accordion `aria-controls`, footer targets) plus one more (blog link text) show the same shape: the pattern was started and not finished. The fix is not more effort so much as one focused completion pass — ideally with a screen reader in hand.

**The happy path outshines the edges.** The main pages are polished and the copy is confident and clear. The 404 page is the sharp exception — the framework default, never touched. Edges and error states deserve the same finish as the core flows, especially on a portfolio that is itself an argument for the owner's design judgment.

**Friction clusters at the moment of action.** The site is strong at *presenting* — clean IA, good scent, clear service descriptions. The two findings that touch the recruiter/client journey (no resume download; the contact page's opening framing — see Appendix C) both sit at the point where a primary user wants to *act*. Smoothing those two moments would have impact out of proportion to the effort.

**What is working well (worth keeping).** Clear, jargon-light writing; a logical and shallow navigation; consistent breadcrumbs and a Back control on detail pages; a current "Last updated May 2026" footer stamp; sensible external-link security (`rel="noopener noreferrer"`); and the accessibility fundamentals listed above. The issues in this report are refinements to a fundamentally sound site.

