### Appendix C — Design Observations

These are suggestions, not defects. They are offered for consideration and were not scored.

- **Contact page opens with a discouraging clause.** The Contact page's first sentence begins "I am not currently looking for new opportunities, but I am always open to connecting…". This is honest and is clearly an intentional choice — and honesty about availability is a virtue. The observation is purely about *ordering*: for the confirmed primary users (recruiters, clients) whose task is to make contact, leading with the openness ("I'm always open to connecting with people in the UX and research community — the fastest way to reach me is…") and placing the availability caveat second would keep the same honesty while not opening on a negative. A small reorder, entirely the owner's call.
- **Homepage whitespace imbalance.** On the Home page, the "How I can help" card grid (left ~two-thirds) ends well above the "From my blog" column (right ~one-third), leaving a tall empty gap on the lower-left at desktop width. Consider balancing the two columns — e.g., a different grid ratio, moving a section, or letting the blog list and cards interleave more evenly.
- **"Back" control on detail pages uses browser history.** The "← Back" control on detail pages is a `<button>` that appears to rely on browser history. A visitor arriving via a direct link or search result who presses it will leave the site. The breadcrumb trail mitigates this (it provides true in-site navigation), so impact is minor — but a history-independent link to the parent section would be more robust.
- **Self-referential homepage copy.** The homepage intro says "My website gives more details about the types of research I do…" while the reader is already on the website. Minor; "This site" or simply rephrasing would read slightly more naturally.
- **External-link new-tab cues vary.** Some external links announce "Opens in a new tab" in their accessible name (Google Scholar, LinkedIn on the Academic/Contact pages); the footer's external links do not. This is folded into Issue #5's consistency point but is worth a site-wide convention check.

### Appendix D — Issues considered and excluded

- **Missing dark-mode support for the main site.** The test browser was in OS dark mode; the site's own pages render light regardless. This is a deliberate, common design choice for a portfolio and was not filed as a defect. It is noted only because it explains why the framework-default 404 page (which *does* honor dark mode) appears black — see Issue #2.
- **No contact form on the Contact page.** The Contact page offers email and LinkedIn but no form. For a portfolio site this is a legitimate, even preferable, choice (email is lower-friction and spam-resistant) and was not filed.
- **`mailto:` links.** Email links open the user's mail application. This is standard and expected; not an issue.
- **Responsive layout.** Not filed as an issue — responsive CSS, a viewport meta tag, and a hamburger toggle are all present in the markup. It is listed instead as a coverage *limitation* (Methodology Note), because the phone-width rendering could not be visually confirmed.
- **Keyboard focus visibility.** Verified working (skip link receives focus first; visible focus outlines on the logo and nav links). Noted here as a positive, not an issue.

